.docname {Architecture Overview}
.include {docs}

CrowdVision is designed as a distributed, event-driven microservices architecture.
By completely separating the frontend client from the backend services—and further isolating those backend services from one another—the platform achieves high fault tolerance, independent scalability, and strict data boundary enforcement.

CrowdVision supports **two deployment models** that share the exact same service code and Docker images, differing only in how traffic is routed into the cluster.

---

## 🐳 Model 1: Docker Compose (Local Development)

All incoming external traffic enters the system through a single **Caddy** reverse-proxy gateway exposed on port `80`.

Caddy acts as the traffic cop: it strips the service prefixes from the URLs and securely proxies the requests to the appropriate target containers running on the internal Docker bridge network.

.mermaid 
    graph TD
        Browser["Browser / Vue Client"] -->|HTTP + WS| Caddy["Caddy Gateway :80"]
        IoT["IoT Sensors (Simulated)"] -->|HTTP POST| Caddy

        subgraph gateway-net [Shared Gateway Network]
            Caddy -->|/auth/*| Auth["auth-service :3000"]
            Caddy -->|/twin/*| Twin["twin-service :3000"]
            Caddy -->|/notification/*| Notif["notification-service :3000"]
            Caddy -->|/socket.io/*| Socket["socket-server :3000"]
            Caddy -->|/sensor/*| Sensor["sensor-service :3000"]

            Notif -->|PUBLISH| Redis[("Redis Broker")]
            Socket -->|SUBSCRIBE| Redis
        end

        subgraph auth-net [Auth Private Network]
            Auth --- AuthDB[("auth-db MongoDB")]
        end

        subgraph twin-net [Twin Private Network]
            Twin --- TwinDB[("twin-db MongoDB")]
        end

        subgraph notification-net [Notification Private Network]
            Notif --- NotifDB[("notification-db MongoDB")]
        end

        subgraph sensor-net [Sensor Private Network]
            Sensor --- SensorDB[("sensor-db MongoDB")]
        end

### Network Segregation & Database Isolation
Each microservice is attached to two networks:
- The shared **gateway-net** (so Caddy can reach them).
- A completely **private database network** (e.g., `auth-net`, `twin-net`, `notification-net`, `sensor-net`).

This physically enforces the Database-per-Service pattern. The Twin Service physically cannot query the Auth Database, ensuring that cross-domain data mutations are impossible.

---

## ☸️ Model 2: Kubernetes (Production / Staging)

In Kubernetes mode, Caddy is replaced by an **nginx Ingress Controller**. The concept is identical — a single entry point that routes traffic by URL path — but the implementation is declarative YAML rather than a `Caddyfile`.

.mermaid 
    graph TD
        Browser["Browser / Vue Client"] -->|HTTP port 80| LB["k3d LoadBalancer"]
        Simulator["Sensor Simulator (external Docker)"] -->|HTTP POST| LB

        LB --> Ingress["nginx Ingress Controller"]

        subgraph crowdvision [Namespace: crowdvision]
            Ingress -->|/auth| AuthSvc["auth-service ClusterIP"]
            Ingress -->|/twin| TwinSvc["twin-service ClusterIP"]
            Ingress -->|/notification| NotifSvc["notification-service ClusterIP"]
            Ingress -->|/sensor| SensorSvc["sensor-service ClusterIP"]
            Ingress -->|/agent| AgentSvc["agent-service ClusterIP"]
            Ingress -->|/socket.io| SocketSvc["socket-service ClusterIP"]
            Ingress -->|/ catch-all| ClientSvc["client ClusterIP"]

            AuthSvc --> AuthPod["auth-service Pod"]
            AuthPod --- AuthDB[("auth-db StatefulSet")]

            TwinSvc --> TwinPod["twin-service Pod"]
            TwinPod --- TwinDB[("twin-db StatefulSet")]

            NotifSvc --> NotifPod["notification-service Pod"]
            NotifPod --- NotifDB[("notification-db StatefulSet")]

            SensorSvc --> SensorPod["sensor-service Pod"]
            SensorPod --- SensorDB[("sensor-db StatefulSet")]

            SocketSvc --> SocketPod["socket-service Pod"]
            SocketPod -->|SUBSCRIBE| RedisPod[("Redis Deployment")]
            NotifPod -->|PUBLISH| RedisPod
        end

A key architectural difference in the Kubernetes model is how the **Sensor Simulator** integrates. Because the simulator is an external Docker container (not a cluster workload), it communicates with the cluster through the load balancer's public port, just like a browser would. See the [External Sensor Simulator](../config/sensor-simulator.qd) page for the full explanation.

For a deep dive into the Kubernetes-specific configuration — StatefulSets, Secrets, Ingress rules, and the cluster setup — see the [Kubernetes Architecture](kubernetes.qd) page.

---

## 🚏 Routing Table

The routing table is identical across both deployment models. The only difference is which component enforces it (Caddy vs nginx Ingress).

.var {headers}
   - External Path Prefix
   - Internal Target Service
   - Purpose

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - `/auth/`
      - `auth-service`
      - Account creation, login, SSO, JWT verification.
    - - `/twin/`
      - `twin-service`
      - Building models, room CRUD operations, spatial data.
    - - `/notification/`
      - `notification-service`
      - Processing sensor events, triggering Web Push alerts.
    - - `/sensor/`
      - `sensor-service`
      - Ingesting time-series sensor readings (people count, temperature).
    - - `/agent/`
      - `agent-service`
      - LLM-powered natural language queries about building data.
    - - `/socket.io/`
      - `socket-service`
      - Maintaining persistent WebSocket connections to the frontend.
    - - `/`
      - `client`
      - Serves the Vue 3 SPA. Catch-all, must be defined last.

.box {Dev Mode} type:{note} 
    🛠️ Developer Mode Only: When running `just dev`, Caddy also exposes `auth-db-express` and `twin-db-express` at `/auth-db-gui/*` and `/twin-db-gui/*`. These are not present in Kubernetes deployments for security reasons.

---

## ⚡ Real-Time Data Flow Pipeline

The most critical flow in CrowdVision is how a physical event (like 50 people walking into a room) triggers a UI update and an emergency notification in a facility manager's browser.
This is achieved using Redis Pub/Sub to decouple the data ingestion from the data broadcast.

.mermaid 
    sequenceDiagram
        participant Sensor as IoT Sensor / Simulator
        participant NotifSvc as Notification Service
        participant Redis as Redis Broker
        participant SocketSvc as Socket Service
        participant VueClient as Vue Frontend

        Sensor->>NotifSvc: POST /notification/push/temperature (Data Payload)
        activate NotifSvc
        Note over NotifSvc: Evaluate limits (overcrowding / maxTemp)
        NotifSvc->>Redis: redisClient.publish('notifications', payload)
        deactivate NotifSvc
        
        activate Redis
        Redis-->>SocketSvc: Message received via SUBSCRIBE
        deactivate Redis
        
        activate SocketSvc
        SocketSvc->>VueClient: io.emit('notification', data)
        deactivate SocketSvc
        
        activate VueClient
        Note over VueClient: socket.ts updates reactive socketState
        VueClient-->>VueClient: NotificationBell badge increments
        VueClient-->>VueClient: PushNotificationToast displays alert
        deactivate VueClient
